s":[{"name":"Godfroy","meanings":["From the Old French name <i>Godefroy</i>, which is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>god</i> ‘god’ (or <i>gōd</i> ‘good’) + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. This was adopted by the Normans, and brought to England by immigrants from the Low Countries and France. It was borne by a Norman saint (  <i>c.</i>1066–1115 ) who became bishop of Amiens. There has been considerable confusion with   Geoffrey ."]},{"name":"Goffin","meanings":["Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metonymic occupational from German <i>Hopfen</i> ‘hops’. The initial <i>g</i> is due to Russian influence, since Russian has no <i>h</i> and alters it to <i>g</i> in borrowed words and names.","French and Walloon: from a pet form of the personal name   Godefroy  .","French and Walloon: possibly also a nickname from a diminutive of Old French <i>goffe</i> ‘heavy, coarse’."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Godeffroy II D'ARLEUX was born in 1093, his father, Hugues III d'Arleux, was 37 and his mother, Louise D’Angres, was 22. He married Clotilde DE WAVRIN about 1127, in France. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1155, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1093–1155":"1093–1155","1104–1173":"1104–1173","–1173":"–1173","1128–1184":"1128–1184","1121–1186":"1121–1186","1056–1116":"1056–1116","1071–1134":"1071–1134","1121":"1121","1186":"1186","1184":"1184","1173":"1173","1093":"1093","1071":"1071","1128":"1128","1116":"1116","1104":"1104","about 1127":"umbes 1127","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1056":"1056","Arleux-en-Gohelle, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Arleux-en-Gohelle, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Arleux-en-Gohelle, Pas-de-Calais, France":"Arleux-en-Gohelle, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Arleux-en-Gohelle, Pas-de-Calais